organismRemarks: Pines are evergreen coniferous trees that cover large areas of the himalayan forest. In the Central Himalaya, P. roxburghii (chir pine) is the most abundant pine species with three slender, triangular needles per bundle which distinguishes it from other pine species in the Himalaya. The tree can attain a height of 30-55m with a diameter up-to 100cm or more. It is distributed mainly between the elevation ranges of 1200-1800m. It is found in association with Shorea robusta and Quercus sp., in lower and upper altitudinal zones respectively, or as pure pine forest stands.     In case of low intensity surface fires, the thick basal bark of mature P. roxburghii trees enables them to prevent complete cambial mortality, also self-pruning of lower branches reduces the likelihood to fire spreading to the canopy. Ability to withstand fire is one of the primary reasons behind the large spread of the species.

These trees provide with wood, gum, fodder, fire material etc. however the variation in forest cover is sightable as compared to 5-10 years before. As observed personally in june 2014 forest fire has become a very very common and regular site leading to blackening and ultimate loss of  habitat of leopards and other animals resulting in their conflict with human population.     Picture also shows terrace farms . Rice, Wheat and bhatt(kind of black pulse) and Finger MIllets is the most preffered crop.

organismRemarks: Pines are conifer trees in the genus Pinus in the family Pinaceae. They are the only genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. Although some authorities claim that there are 115 species of pine, different authorities generally agree that there are between 105 and 125 species.     Pines are native to a majority of the Northern Hemisphere and have been introduced throughout most temperate and subtropical regions of the world where they are grown as timber and cultivated as ornamental plants in parks and gardens. In Uttarakhand it is also commenly used as timber and firewood.     http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pine

name: Pinus roxburghii Sarg.
higherClassification: Plantae | Tracheophyta | Pinopsida | Pinales | Pinaceae | Pinus | Pinus roxburghii Sarg.
organismRemarks: Pinus roxburghii (known as chir pine) is a species of pine native to the Himalayas, and named after William Roxburgh.It generally occurs in the Himalaya  from 500–2,000 metres and occasionally up to 2,300 meters.     I have seen many hill ranges (from Pithoragarh to Champawat) having chir pine forests which were burning continuously for weeks long during my visit in the region in the month of May-June,2012,the forest fire is the big threat for the pine forest which destroy the thousand of hectares pine forest in this region every year.     The fires usually break out between March and June (fire season) in the coniferous chir pine forests in the 1000-1800m (altitude) range, with many of them caused by human interference in the forests.This year too, forests fires have been raging in thousands of hectares in the State. see the report published in the Pioneer & times on forest fire - http://dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/70742-forest-fires-threaten-states-environment.html     http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/flora-fauna/A-fiery-summer-in-Uttarakhand/articleshow/14471314.cms     The accumulating carpet of needles on the forest floor under these trees is the big reason of catching the accidental fire.

name: Pinus wallichiana A.B.Jacks.
identificationRemarks: This pine species is much planted as ornamental tree in gardens and parks in Europe and elsewhere, good to have this observation at native range. English term "Bhutan pine" is misleading (as most E. names turn out to be), since the closest related, now separated species (not by all botanists!) Pinus bhutanica, more distributed in eastern part of Himalayan Mountains, deserved this name. P. wallichiana might better be named "Wallich's pine" or "Himalayan pine", we do call the species "Tränenkiefer" (since resin drops hanging at large cones reminding on tears) or "Himalayakiefer" in German.

name: Pinus wallichiana A.B.Jacks.
occurrenceRemarks: A large tree with pin like leaves which helps it tolerate snow, the fruit is often coloured and used as a decorative article by locals. In India there is large scale removal of oil from the tree which slowly dries and kills the whole tree. Maybe introduction of proper techniques is required to help save the trees. Usually the tree is scratched at the bottom on one side this side gives oil for 2 years min. then the other side is scratched and so on . After the third side is scratched and the oil is removed, the tree becomes useless for the collectors and eventually dies. Very sad.
